  "prompt": "Can a set be both a subset and a proper subset?",
  "response": "Yes, a set can be both a subset and a proper subset, depending on the context.\n\n1. **Subset**: A set \\( A \\) is considered a subset of a set \\( B \\) (denoted \\( A \\subseteq B \\)) if every element of \\( A \\) is also an element of \\( B \\). This includes the possibility that \\( A \\) and \\( B \\) are exactly the same set.\n\n2. **Proper Subset**: A set \\( A \\) is a proper subset of a set \\( B \\) (denoted \\( A \\subset B \\)) if \\( A \\) is a subset of \\( B \\) but not equal to \\( B \\). In other words, there must be at least one element in \\( B \\) that is not in \\( A \\).\n\nBased on these definitions, a set cannot be both a subset and a proper subset of another set at the same time if they are exactly the same. However, if \\( A \\) is a subset of \\( B \\) and is not equal to \\( B \\), then it can be described as both just a subset (because it meets the criterion for being a subset) and simultaneously a proper subset (since it is not equal to \\( B \\)). In summary:\n\n- If \\( A = B \\), then \\( A \\) is only a subset (not a proper subset).\n- If \\( A \\subset B \\) (and therefore \\( A \\) is not equal to \\( B \\)), then \\( A \\) is both a subset and a proper subset of \\( B \\).",
